    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1924-01-04T07:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1924-01-04T07:00:00-05:00" n="664"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d664">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">890d.01A71: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in France</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Herrick</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Paraphrase]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Paris</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1924-01-04T12:00:00+00:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">January 4, 1924—noon</hi>
                        </date>.<lb/>[Received January 4—9:22 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>3. The French Foreign Office does not want to insert in mandate convention
                    mention of our extradition treaty of 1909<note n="2" xml:id="d664fn2">Malloy,
                            <hi rend="italic">Treaties</hi>, 1910–1923, vol. <hi rend="smallcaps"
                            >iii</hi>, p. 2580.</note> … The Foreign Office states that we are fully
                    protected by article 7 of the mandate<note n="3" xml:id="d664fn3">Quoted in the
                        convention between the United States and France, <hi rend="italic"
                        >post</hi>, <ref target="#pg_742">p. 742</ref>.</note> …</p>
                <p>Study is being made of the question of consular conventions. I do not expect
                    there will be any opposition unless there is some special privilege granted in
                    our consular convention of 1853<note n="4" xml:id="d664fn4">Malloy, <hi
                            rend="italic">Treaties</hi>, 1776–1909, vol. <hi rend="smallcaps"
                        >i</hi>, p. 528.</note> which the French might have to extend to everyone
                    else if it was mentioned in our convention. I was questioned by Fromageot<note
                        n="5" xml:id="d664fn5">Legal Adviser in the French Foreign Office.</note>
                    about our convention regarding Palestine and replied that I was uninformed.
                    Fromageot is going to confer with Hurst<note n="6" xml:id="d664fn6">Legal
                        Adviser in the British Foreign Office.</note> who is coming Sunday for the
                    Claims Commission. I anticipate that I will be informed afterwards that the
                    French are ready to sign our convention.</p>
                <p>Do you accept French view on extradition? To me it appears reasonable.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Herrick</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
